# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apo-drink
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apo-drink/aam-panna] Unripe mango is a rich source of pectin, which gradually diminishes after the formation of the stone.
[src:apo-drink/aam-panna] Unripe mango is sour in taste because of the presence of oxalic, citric and malic acids.
[src:apo-drink/aam-panna] Aam panna or Aam Jhora, which is prepared using raw mangoes, cumin, and an assortment of other spices, quenches thirst and prevents the excessive loss of sodium chloride and iron during summer due to excessive sweating.
[src:apo-drink/aam-panna] The drink is mainly consumed in north India and Pakistan is considered beneficial in the treatment of gastrointestinal disorders.
[src:apo-drink/aam-panna] It is also a good source of vitamin B1 and B2, niacin, and vitamin C.
[src:apo-drink/aam-panna] In Indian and Pakistani culture, it is regarded as a tonic believed to increase resistance against tuberculosis, anemia, cholera and dysentery.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] The Ahom people established the Ahom kingdom and ruled parts of the Brahmaputra river valley in the present day Indian state of Assam between the 13th and the 18th centuries.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] The language was the court language of the kingdom, until it began to be replaced by the Assamese language in the 17th century.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Since the early 18th century, there have been no native speakers of the language, though extensive manuscripts in the language still exist today.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] The tonal system of the language is entirely lost.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] The language was only partially known by a small group of traditional priests of the Ahom religion, and it was being used only for ceremonial or ritualistic purposes.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] There have been efforts to revive the language in recent times.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] A reconstructed version is taught in various schools in Assam by AHSEC and universities like Gauhati University and Dibrugarh University.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Tai Ahom is classified in a Northwestern subgrouping of Southwestern Tai owing to close affinities with Shan, Khamti and, more distantly, Thai.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Ahom is distinct from but closely related to Aiton, which is still spoken in Assam to this day.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] When speaking and writing Ahom, much is dependent upon context and the audience interpretation.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Multiple parts of the sentence can be left out; verb and adjectives will remain, but other parts of speech, especially pronouns, can be dropped.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Verbs do not have tenses, and nouns do not have plurals.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Time periods can be identified by adverbs, strings of verbs, or auxiliaries placed before the verb.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Ahom, like other Tai languages, uses classifiers to identify categories, and repetitions of words to express idiomatic expressions.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] However, the expressions, classifiers, pronouns, and other sentence particles vary between the Tai languages descended from Proto-Tai, making Tai languages mutually unintelligible.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] The Ahom people and their language originated in Yunnan in south-west China.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] They migrated from the border between northern Vietnam and the Guangxi province of China, to the Hukawng Valley, along the upper reaches of the Chindwin river, northern Burma.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] In the 13th century, they crossed the Patkai Range. and settled in the Brahmaputra River valley, in Northeast India.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] After increasing their power in Upper Assam, the Ahom people extended their power to the south of the river Brahmaputra and east of the river Dikho, which corresponds to the modern day districts of Dibrugarh and Sibsagar, Assam, where the Ahom still reside today.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Tai Ahom was the exclusive court language of the Ahom kingdom, where it was used to write state-histories or 'Buranjis'.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] In the 16th and 17th centuries, the small Ahom community expanded their rule dramatically toward the west and they successfully saw off challenges from the Mughal Empire and other invaders.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] The rapid expansion resulted in the Ahom people becoming a small minority in their own kingdom, of which they kept control.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] During the 17th century, the Assamese language entered the Ahom court and co-existed with the Tai Ahom for some time before finally replacing it.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Eventually the Ahom peasants too adopted the Assamese language over the Ahom language for secular purposes, while Ahom was restricted to religious use by Ahom priests.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] The everyday usage of Ahom language ceased completely by the early 19th century.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Although the language is no longer spoken, the exhaustive 1795 Ahom-Assamese lexicon known as the *Bar Amra* preserves the lexical forms of the language towards the end of the Ahom Kingdom.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] The language today is used chiefly for liturgical purposes, and is no longer used in daily life.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] While the written language (and ritualistic chants) survive in a vast number of written manuscripts, Ahom is therefore usually regarded as a dead language.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] It retains cultural significance and is used for religious chants and to read literature.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] This is complicated however by the fact that the phonology with its tone system has been completely lost, because the Ahom script does not mark tone and under-specifies vowel contrasts, which obscures the meaning of words as tones are important to distinguish the meaning of words in tonal languages.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Fabricated samples of the Ahom script delayed translation of legitimate Ahom texts.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Several publications were created based on the fabricated samples, leading to incorrect grammatical analysis and dictionary resources that acted as a barrier to future researchers.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] A later translation of *Ahom Buranji*, a major Ahom script was provided by Golap Chandra Barua, the same man responsible for fabricating samples of translated Ahom script.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] It was discovered years later, by Professor Prasert na Nagara, that the translation was unreliable.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Despite these difficulties, along with the lack of native speakers and specific text, studies in Ahom have prevailed, and certain available scripts have been translated and transliterated, using known words, characters and context.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] In 1954, at a meeting of Ahom people at Patsaku, Sibsagar District, the Tai Historical and Cultural Society of Assam was founded.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Since the late 1960s, Ahom culture and traditions have witnessed a revival.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] In 1981 the Eastern Tai Literary Organization has been founded in Dhemaji, which produced language text books and publications in the Ahom script.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Schools in Dibrugarh and Sibsagar districts started offering Tai language classes, teaching a mix of Tai Ahom, Phakey, Khamti and Central Thai.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] The scholar Terwiel notes that the view of the Ahom language being a dead language is hotly contested by Ahom priests and spokesmen of the revival movement.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] According to them, the language did not die out because Ahom priests still use the language for religious purposes.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Some even claim that the priestly class speaks Ahom as their mother tongue.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Upon further investigation, it was determined that the priests could decipher the Ahom script and read the words aloud.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] However, because they did not know any tones, they did not have any idea of the meaning of the words except for the simplest expressions.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] According to Terwiel, there are great differences between the old Ahom language of the manuscripts, which is easily recognizable as a Tai language, and what the revivalists call Ahom, which does not follow the rules of Tai grammar.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] It has also changed greatly regarding semantics, literally translating Assamese into Tai words, which leads to sentences which do not make sense to any Tai speaker.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Terwiel therefore calls this revived language 'pseudo-Ahom'.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Nevertheless, this revived language has been used passionately by revitalists and many neologisms have been created.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] The demand for translation into Tai Ahom led to the creation of the first adequate modern dictionary by Nomal Chandra Gogoi in 1987, titled *The Assamese-English-Tai Dictionary*.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] This dictionary allowed a reader to find the translation of 9,000 Assamese words into English and Tai.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] This dictionary filled in missing gaps of the Ahom vocabulary with Aiton and Khamti words and if those were not available, Lanna and Thai words were used.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] The result was a hodgepodge of multiple Tai languages, that was only linked to the Ahom language by the Ahom script in which the dictionary entries were written.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] The scholar Terwiel recommended in 1992 to base neo-Ahom on the grammar and tones of the very closely related Aiton language, which is still spoken in Assam.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Summarizing, the revivalists use a language consisting of a mixture of Tai words from multiple Tai languages, overlaid on an Assamese grammatical base.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] In 1999, the scholar Morey reported that Ahom priests have resorted to compounding words to differentiate between words that are homophones in the revived language, since Ahom lost its tone system.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] For example in old Ahom, the word *su* for tiger and *su* for shirt would have sounded differently by pronouncing them with a different tone.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] In revived Ahom, they are now differentiated by compounding them with another word: *tu* for animal and *pha* for cloth respectively.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Subsequently, *tu su* and *pha su* can be differentiated.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] An effort has been made to revive the language by following the phonology of existing sister languages, especially Tai-Aiton and Tai-Phake.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] The Institute of Tai Studies and Research (ITSAR), is a Tai Ahom language teaching institute in Moran, Sivasagar, Assam, India, established in 2001 and affiliated to Dibrugarh University.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] It offers a one-year Tai Ahom language diploma course and a three-month certificate course in spoken Tai Ahom.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Other initiatives have been taken, such as workshops and language classes.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] In 2019, the 'Tai Ahom Yuva Chatra Sanmilan, Assam' (TAYCSA), demanded that the Tai Ahom language be included in the school curriculum of the state of Assam.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] They also demanded the creation of a two-year diploma course in Mahdavdeva University.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] An online dictionary containing nearly 5,000 entries (see External links) has been created by analyzing old manuscripts, especially the Bar Amra.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] A descriptive grammar of Ahom, based on the grammar found in old manuscripts, is being worked on.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] A sketch has been released, titled “A Sketch of Tai Ahom” by Stephen Morey.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] The semi-vowel /w/ is missing from the system, however it is an allophone of /b/ that occurs only in the word final position.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Consonants found in the word final position are: /p, t, k, m, n, ŋ, j, b [w]/.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Vowels can occur in syllable medial and final positions only.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] The language had a tone system, but because the Ahom script did not spell out any tones, the tones are now unknown.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Ahom uses the proximal demonstrative *nai* meaning 'this' and the distal demonstrative *nan* meaning 'that'.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Tai Ahom mainly used an SVO word order, but an SOV word order has also been attested.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Classifiers are used when forming plurals, counting entities and when specifically referring to one single entity.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Some classifiers are: 'kun' (used for persons), 'tu' (used for animals) and 'an' (general).
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] For example 'khai song tu' means two buffalo, where 'khai' means buffalo, 'song' means two and 'tu' is the classifier for animals.
[src:apo-drink/ahom-language] Below is a comparative table of Ahom and other Tai languages.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] An **alcoholic beverage** (also called an **alcoholic drink** or **strong drink**) is any drink that contains alcohol, a central nervous system depressant.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] They are typically divided into three classes: beers, wines, and spirits; with alcohol content typically between 3% and 50%.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The exact amount on which a beverage is considered alcoholic differs by country, with some considering drinks containing less than 0.5% to be non-alcoholic.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] These beverages are primarily consumed for the psychoactive effects that they produce.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Many societies have a distinct drinking culture, in which alcoholic drinks are integrated into parties.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Most countries have laws regulating the production, sale, and consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Some regulations require the labeling of the percentage alcohol content (as ABV or proof) and the use of a warning label.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Some countries ban the consumption of alcoholic drinks, but they are legal in most parts of the world.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The temperance movement advocates against the consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The global alcoholic drink industry exceeded $1.5 trillion in 2017.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Alcohol is one of the most widely used recreational drugs in the world, and about 33% of all humans currently drink alcohol.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In 2015, among Americans, 86% of adults had consumed alcohol at some point, with 70% drinking it in the last year and 56% in the last month.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Several other animals are affected by alcohol similarly to humans and, once they consume it, will consume it again if given the opportunity; however, humans are the only species known to produce alcoholic drinks intentionally.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Alcohol is a depressant, a class of psychoactive drug that slows down activity in the central nervous system.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In low doses it causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death (an overdose).
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Long-term use can lead to alcoholism, an increased risk of developing several types of cancer, cardiovascular disease, and physical dependence.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Alcohol is classified as a group 1 carcinogen.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Discovery of late Stone Age jugs suggests that intentionally fermented drinks existed at least as early as the Neolithic period.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The oldest verifiable brewery has been found in a prehistoric burial site in a cave near Haifa in modern-day Israel.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Researchers have found residue of 13,000-year-old beer that they think might have been used for ritual feasts to honor the dead.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The traces of a wheat-and-barley-based alcohol were found in stone mortars carved into the cave floor.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The Carmona Wine Urn is a first century Roman glass urn containing intact wine.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Beer was likely brewed from barley as early as 13,000 years ago in the Middle East.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Pliny the Elder wrote about the *golden age* of winemaking in Rome, the 2nd century BCE (200–100 BCE), when vineyards were planted.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Examination and analysis of ancient pottery jars from the neolithic village of Jiahu in the Henan province of northern China revealed residue left behind by the alcoholic drinks they had once contained.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Chemical analysis of the residue confirmed that a fermented drink made of grape and hawthorn fruit wine, honey mead and rice beer was being produced in 7000–5600 BC.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The residence in which the jar was discovered and other houses in the same village were found to contain many such jars suggesting that wine was an important part of their diet.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The earliest evidence of winemaking was dated at 6,000 to 5,800 BCE in Georgia in the South Caucasus.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Excavations surrounding Neolithic settlements there unearthed grape pips of a variety which differed from those of wild grapes, pointing to deliberate cultivation, and local pottery dated to approximately 6000 BCE was decorated with depictions of celebrating human figures.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The earliest clear chemical evidence of beer produced from barley dates to about 3500–3100 BCE, from the site of Godin Tepe in the Zagros Mountains of western Iran.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] At a site dating to 3100-2900 BCE, a pottery vessel containing residue of alcoholic barley was discovered, possibly serving as the earliest proof of beer brewing in the region.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] However, it is unclear whether it was meant for intoxication or nourishment.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Celtic people were known to have been making types of alcoholic cider as early as 3000 BCE. and wine was consumed in Classical Greece at breakfast or at symposia, and in the 1st century BCE.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Archaeological finds as well as ancient documentation serve as testimony to the popularity and abundance of alcohol in the Sumerian society.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Access to alcohol was regulated, the social elite indulged in it and it served as sacrificial offerings to the gods.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In Sumerian culture Alcohol was also a means for happiness.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In the epic of Gilgamesh, Enkidu the wild man drinks seven jugs of beer, becomes elated and sings with joy.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Other characters routinely drink water, but drink alcohol when celebrating.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] During the new year celebrations, the ceremonial reenactment of the drunken union between the king of Uruk and the high priestess of Ishtar, the goddess of procreation, symbolized the genesis of Ninkasi, the beer goddess.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A hymn to Ninkasi gives a detailed description of hash production in Sumer, involving the fermentation of bread and the addition of grapes and honey, resulting in an unfiltered brew drunk through straws.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In Hierakonpolis, Egypt, the remains of a brewery dating to circa 3400 BCE was unearthed, with an estimated yield of up to 1135 litres (300 US gallons) of brew per day.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Wine was a symbol of power and was imported from abroad, hence it was reserved for royalty and the social elite, while beer was the drink of common society.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In the tomb of the Scorpion king, who ruled Hierakonpolis when the brewery was built, approximately 700 wine jars imported from the southern Levant were unearthed.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Financial documents recorded that the daily ration of beer for the workers who built the pyramids of Giza was nearly 4 litres, and modern reproductions of the ancient recipe produced a brew weighed in at 5 percent ABV, the same as that of the modern day pint.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Despite the many Egyptian sources describing brewing methods, very few discuss intoxication.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In honor of this deed a red coloured alcohol was drunk in large quantities during the festival causing similar intoxicated stupors.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Osiris was also associated with wine, as his death and resurrection were compared to the cycle of withering and regrowth of the vine during the winter and spring.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Multiple amphorae were discovered in the graves of pharaohs and elites as provisions for the afterlife and as offerings to Osiris, commonly with labels detailing their origin, maker, and date.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Over time, labels eventually included assessments of quality as well, such as "good," (*nfr*) "very good," (*nfr nfr*) or "very very good," (*nfr nfr nfr*) alongside provenance, and it was believed that certain vintages improved with age.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Archaeological findings reveal that some wines buried with their owners were several decades old, exceeding the average life expectancy, and therefore assumed to have outlived their creators.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Medieval Muslim chemists such as Jābir ibn Ḥayyān (Latin: Geber, ninth century) and Abū Bakr al-Rāzī (Latin: Rhazes, c.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] 865–925) experimented extensively with the distillation of various substances.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The distillation of wine is attested in Arabic works attributed to al-Kindī (c.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] 872–950), and in the 28th book of al-Zahrāwī's (Latin: Abulcasis, 936–1013) *Kitāb al-Taṣrīf* (later translated into Latin as *Liber servatoris*).
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] 12th century: The process of distillation spread from the Middle East to Italy, where distilled alcoholic drinks were recorded in the mid-12th century.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In Italy, the works of Taddeo Alderotti (1223–1296) describe a method for concentrating alcohol involving repeated fractional distillation through a water-cooled still.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] By the early 14th century, distilled alcoholic drinks had spread throughout the European continent.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Distillation spread to Ireland and Scotland no later than the 15th century, as did the common European practice of distilling "aqua vitae", primarily for medicinal purposes.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Drinking hard liquor was common occurrence in early nineteenth-century United States.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The Whiskey Rebellion (also known as the Whiskey Insurrection) was a violent tax protest in the United States beginning in 1791 and ending in 1794 during the presidency of George Washington.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The so-called "whiskey tax" was the first tax imposed on a domestic product by the newly formed federal government.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Beer was difficult to transport and spoiled more easily than rum and whiskey.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The Rum Rebellion of 1808 was a *coup d'état* in the then-British penal colony of New South Wales, staged by the New South Wales Corps in order to depose Governor William Bligh.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Australia's first and only military coup, its name derives from the illicit rum trade of early Sydney, over which the 'Rum Corps', as it became known, maintained a monopoly.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] During the first half of the 19th century, it was widely referred to in Australia as the Great Rebellion.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The alcohol monopoly system has a long history in various countries, often implemented to limit the availability and consumption of alcohol for public health and social welfare reasons.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The alcohol monopoly was created in the Swedish town of Falun in 1850, to prevent overconsumption and reduce the profit motive for sales of alcohol.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] It later went all over the country in 1905 when the Swedish parliament ordered all sales of vodka to be done via local alcohol monopolies.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In 1894, the Russian Empire established a state monopoly on vodka, which became a major source of revenue for the Russian government.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Beer is a beverage fermented from grain mash.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] It is typically made from barley or a blend of several grains and flavored with hops.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Most beer is naturally carbonated as part of the fermentation process.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] If the fermented mash is distilled, then the drink becomes a spirit.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Beer is the most consumed alcoholic beverage in the world.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Cider or cyder (/ˈsaɪdər/ *SY-dər*) is a fermented alcoholic drink made from any fruit juice; apple juice (traditional and most common), peaches, pears ("Perry" cider) or other fruit.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Cider alcohol content varies from 1.2% ABV to 8.5% or more in traditional English ciders.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In some regions, cider may be called "apple wine".
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Fermented water is an ethanol-based water solution with approximately 15-17% ABV without sweet reserve.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Fermented water is exclusively fermented with white sugar, yeast, and water.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Fermented water is clarified after the fermentation to produce a colorless or off-white liquid with no discernible taste other than that of ethanol.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Mead (/miːd/), also called hydromel, is an alcoholic drink made by fermenting honey with water, sometimes with various fruits, spices, grains, or hops.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The alcoholic content of mead may range from as low as 3% ABV to more than 20%.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The defining characteristic of mead is that the majority of the drink's fermentable sugar is derived from honey.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Pulque is the Mesoamerican fermented drink made from the "honey water" of maguey, *Agave americana*.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Pulque can be distilled to produce tequila or Mezcal.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Rice wine is an alcoholic drink fermented and possibly distilled from rice, consumed in East Asia, Southeast Asia and South Asia.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Sake, huangjiu, mijiu, and cheongju are popular examples of East Asian rice wine.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Wine is a fermented beverage most commonly produced from grapes.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Wine involves a longer fermentation process than beer and often a long aging process (months or years), resulting in an alcohol content of 9%–16% ABV.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Sparkling wines such as French Champagne, Catalan Cava and Italian Prosecco are also made from grapes, with a secondary fermentation.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Fruit wines are made from fruits other than grapes, such as plums, cherries, or apples.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Wine, beer, and spirits are produced through the activity of yeasts, a group of roughly 160 species of single-celled fungi, some of which are beneficial, while others are associated with food spoilage or human disease.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The most commonly used yeasts in fermentation and baking belong to the genus *Saccharomyces*, whose name means "sugar fungus".
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] These organisms are cultivated both for their role in generating flavors and aromas considered desirable, and for their ability to inhibit the growth of competing microbes which would otherwise infect food.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Their production of alcohol is linked to their capacity to function with minimal oxygen.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Distilled beverages (also called liquors or spirit drinks) are alcoholic drinks produced by distilling (i.e., concentrating by distillation) ethanol produced by means of fermenting grain, fruit, or vegetables.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Unsweetened, distilled, alcoholic drinks that have an alcohol content of at least 20% ABV are called *spirits*.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] For the most common distilled drinks, such as whisky (or whiskey) and vodka, the alcohol content is around 40%.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The term *hard liquor* is used in North America to distinguish distilled drinks from undistilled ones (implicitly weaker).
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Brandy, gin, mezcal, rum, tequila, vodka, whisky (or whiskey), baijiu, shōchū and soju are examples of distilled drinks.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Distilling concentrates the alcohol and eliminates some of the congeners.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Freeze distillation concentrates ethanol along with methanol and fusel alcohols (fermentation by-products partially removed by distillation) in applejack.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Fortified wine is wine, such as port or sherry, to which a distilled beverage (usually brandy) has been added.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Fortified wine is distinguished from spirits made from wine in that spirits are produced by means of distillation, while fortified wine is wine that has had a spirit added to it.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Many different styles of fortified wine have been developed, including port, sherry, madeira, marsala, commandaria, and the aromatized wine vermouth.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Rectified spirit, also called "neutral grain spirit", is alcohol which has been purified by means of "rectification" (i.e. repeated distillation).
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The term *neutral* refers to the spirit's lack of flavor that would have been present if the mash ingredients had been distilled to a lower level of alcoholic purity.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Rectified spirit also lacks any flavoring added to it after distillation (as is done, for example, with gin).
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Other kinds of spirits, such as whiskey, (or whisky) are distilled to a lower alcohol percentage to preserve the flavor of the mash.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Rectified spirit is a clear, colorless, flammable liquid that may contain as much as 95% ABV.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] It is often used for medicinal purposes.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] It may be a grain spirit, or it may be made from other plants.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] It is used in mixed drinks, liqueurs, and tinctures, and also as a household solvent.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In the alcoholic drinks industry, congeners are substances produced during fermentation.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] These substances include small amounts of chemicals such as occasionally desired alcohols, like propanol and 3-methyl-1-butanol, as well as compounds that are never desired such as acetone, acetaldehyde and glycols.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Congeners are responsible for most of the taste and aroma of distilled alcoholic drinks and contribute to the taste of non-distilled drinks.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] It has been suggested that these substances contribute to the symptoms of a hangover.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Tannins are congeners found in wine in the presence of phenolic compounds.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Wine tannins add bitterness, have a drying sensation, taste herbaceous, and are often described as astringent.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Wine tannins add balance, complexity, structure and make a wine last longer, so they play an important role in the aging of wine.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Top-shelf liquor (or "premium liquor") is a term used in marketing to describe higher-priced alcoholic beverages, typically stored on the top shelves within bars.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A mixed drink is a beverage in which two or more ingredients are mixed, and is often alcoholic.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Alcohol powder or powdered alcohol or dry alcohol is a product generally made using micro-encapsulation.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] When reconstituted with water, the powder becomes an alcoholic drink.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A well drink or rail drink is an alcoholic beverage or mixed drink made using the lower-cost liquors stored within easy reach of the bartender in the bar's "speed rail", "speed rack", or "well", a rack or shelf at a lower level than the bar that the bartender uses to prepare drinks.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The average number of people who drink as of 2016 was 39% for males and 25% for females (2.4 billion people in total).
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Females on average drink 0.7 drinks per day while males drink 1.7 drinks per day.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The rates of drinking varies significantly in different areas of the world.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Drinking games are games which involve the consumption of alcoholic beverages and often enduring the subsequent intoxication resulting from them.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Evidence of the existence of drinking games dates back to antiquity.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Drinking games have been banned at some institutions, particularly colleges and universities.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A drinking song is a song sung while drinking an alcoholic beverage.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A beer garden (German: *Biergarten*) is an outdoor area in which beer and food are served, typically at shared tables shaded by trees.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A beer hall (German: *Bierpalast, Bierhalle*) is a large pub that specializes in beer.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A cider house is an establishment that sells alcoholic cider for consumption on the premises.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Some cider houses also sell cider "to go", for consumption off the premises.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A traditional cider house was often little more than a room in a farmhouse or cottage, selling locally fermented cider.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] An ouzeri (Greek *ουζερί* IPA: [uzeˈri]) is a type of Greek tavern which serves ouzo (a Greek liquor) and mezedes (small finger foods).
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Pulquerías (or pulcherías) are a type of tavern in Mexico that specialize in serving an alcoholic beverage known as pulque.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A tiki bar is a themed drinking establishment that serves elaborate cocktails, especially rum-based mixed drinks such as the Mai Tai and Zombie cocktails.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Tiki bars are aesthetically defined by their tiki culture décor which is based upon a romanticized conception of tropical cultures, most commonly Polynesian.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A toddy shop is a drinking establishment seen in some parts of India (particularly Kerala) where palm toddy, a mildly alcoholic beverage made from the sap of palm trees, is served along with food.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A wine bar is a tavern-like business focusing on selling wine, rather than liquor or beer.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A typical feature of many wine bars is a wide selection of wines available by the glass.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Some wine bars are profiled on wines of a certain type of origin, such as Italian wine or Champagne.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] While many wine bars are private "stand-alone" establishments, in some cases, wine bars are associated with a specific wine retailer or other outlet of wine, to provide additional marketing for that retailer's wine portfolio.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In countries where licensing regulations allow this, some wine bars also sell the wines they serve, and effectively function as a hybrid between a wine shop and a wine bar.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A beer festival is an event at which a variety of beers are available for purchase.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] There may be a theme, for instance beers from a particular area, or a particular brewing style such as winter ales.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Annual wine festivals celebrate viticulture and usually occur after the harvest of the grapes which, in the northern hemisphere, generally falls at the end of September and runs until well into October or later.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] They are common in most wine regions around the world and are to be considered in the tradition of other harvest festivals.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Beer tasting is a way to learn more about the history, ingredients, and production of beer, as well as different beer styles, hops, yeast, and beer presentation.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A common approach is to analyze the appearance, smell, and taste of the beer, and then make a final judgment on the beer's quality.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] There are various scales used by beer journalists and experts to rate beer, such as the 1-20 scale used by British sommelier Jancis Robinson and the 1-100 scale used by American sommelier Joshua M.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Professional organizations like the Wine & Spirit Education Trust often rate beer using verbal grades ranging from "faulty" to "outstanding" on a 1-5 scale.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Wine tasting, on the other hand, is the sensory examination and evaluation of wine.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] While the practice of wine tasting is ancient, a more formalized methodology has been established since the 14th century.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Modern, professional wine tasters use specialized terminology to describe the range of perceived flavors, aromas, and general characteristics of a wine.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] More informal, recreational tasting may involve similar terminology, but with a less analytical process and a more general, personal appreciation of the wine.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Craft beer tourism refers to tourism where the primary motivation of travel is to visit a brewery, beer festival, beer related activity or other event that allows attendees to experience all aspects of the craft beer-making, consuming and purchasing process.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Enotourism, oenotourism, wine tourism, or **vinitourism** refers to tourism whose purpose is or includes the tasting, consumption or purchase of wine, often at or near the source.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Where other types of tourism are often passive in nature, enotourism can consist of visits to wineries, tasting wines, vineyard walks, or even taking an active part in the harvest.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] An apéritif is any alcoholic beverage usually served before a meal to stimulate the appetite, while a digestif is any alcoholic beverage served after a meal for the stated purpose of improving digestion.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Fortified wine, liqueurs, and dry champagne are common apéritifs.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Because apéritifs are served before dining, they are usually dry rather than sweet.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] One example is Cinzano, a brand of vermouth.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Digestifs include brandy, fortified wines and herb-infused spirits (Drambuie).
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Pure ethanol tastes bitter to humans; some people also describe it as sweet.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] However, ethanol is also a moderately effective solvent for many fatty substances and essential oils.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] This facilitates the use of flavoring and coloring compounds in alcoholic drinks as a taste mask, especially in distilled drinks.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Some flavors may be naturally present in the beverage's raw material.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Beer and wine may also be flavored before fermentation, and spirits may be flavored before, during, or after distillation.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Sometimes flavor is obtained by allowing the beverage to stand for months or years in oak barrels, usually made of American or French oak.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A few brands of spirits may also have fruit or herbs inserted into the bottle at the time of bottling.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Wine is important in cuisine not just for its value as an accompanying beverage, but as a flavor agent, primarily in stocks and braising, since its acidity lends balance to rich savory or sweet dishes.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Wine sauce is an example of a culinary sauce that uses wine as a primary ingredient.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Natural wines may exhibit a broad range of alcohol content, from below 9% to above 16% ABV, with most wines being in the 12.5–14.5% range.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Fortified wines (usually with brandy) may contain 20% alcohol or more.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Vinegar (*vyn egre*; sour wine) is an aqueous solution of acetic acid and trace compounds that may include flavorings.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Vinegar typically contains from 5% to 18% acetic acid by volume.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Usually, the acetic acid is produced by a double fermentation, converting simple sugars to ethanol using yeast and ethanol to acetic acid using acetic acid bacteria.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Wine and food matching is the process of pairing food dishes with wine to enhance the dining experience.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In many cultures, wine has had a long history of being a staple at the dinner table and in some ways both the winemaking and culinary traditions of a region will have evolved together over the years.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Rather than following a set of rules, local cuisines were paired simply with local wines.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The modern "art" of food pairings is a relatively recent phenomenon, fostering an industry of books and media with guidelines for pairings of particular foods and wine.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In the restaurant industry, sommeliers are often present to make food pairing recommendations for the guest.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The main concept behind pairings is that certain elements (such as texture and flavor) in both food and wine interact with each other, and thus finding the right combination of these elements will make the entire dining experience more enjoyable.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] However, taste and enjoyment are very subjective and what may be a "textbook perfect" pairing for one taster could be less enjoyable to another.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Alcoholic beverages are typical offerings for the folk saint Maximón, and Santa Muerte.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Both folk saints have been described as narco-saints.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A libation is a ritual pouring of a liquid, or grains such as rice, as an offering to a deity or spirit, or in memory of the dead.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] It was common in many religions of antiquity and continues to be offered in cultures today.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Wine or other alcoholic drinks are often used for libation.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Libation was part of ancient Egyptian society where it was a drink offering to honor and please the various divinities, sacred ancestors, humans present and humans who are alive but not physically present, as well as the environment.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] It is suggested that libation originated somewhere in the upper Nile Valley and spread out to other regions of Africa and the world.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In the Quechua and Aymara cultures of the South American Andes, it is common to pour a small amount of one's beverage on the ground before drinking as an offering to the Pachamama, or Mother Earth.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] This especially holds true when drinking Chicha, an alcoholic beverage unique to this part of the world.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The libation ritual is commonly called *challa* and is performed quite often, usually before meals and during celebrations.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The amount of sacramental wine consumed during the Eucharist is typically limited to a single sip or small portion, which does not result in a measurable increase in the participant's blood alcohol content.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] This controlled and symbolic consumption of the sacramental wine is an integral part of the Eucharistic rite and does not lead to intoxication.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] According to the Catholic Church, the sacramental wine used in the Eucharist must contain alcohol.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Some Evangelical Lutheran Church in America (ELCA) congregations make grape juice available for children and those who are abstaining from alcohol and some will accommodate those with an allergy to wheat, gluten, or grapes.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A tincture is typically an extract of plant or animal material dissolved in ethanol (ethyl alcohol).
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Solvent concentrations of 25–60% are common, but may run as high as 90%.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In chemistry, a tincture is a solution that has ethanol as its solvent.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In herbal medicine, alcoholic tinctures are made with various ethanol concentrations, which should be at least 20% alcohol for preservation purposes.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A flaming drink is often ignited for aesthetic and entertainment purposes.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Alcoholic beverage may be consumed to celebrate observances such as the International Beer Day, International whisk(e)y day, or National Vodka Day.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] They also drink them for social events like International Women's Collaboration Brew Day, where people come together to make beer.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Alcohol measurements are units of measurement for determining amounts of beverage alcohol.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Alcohol concentration in beverages is commonly expressed as alcohol by volume (ABV), ranging from less than 0.1% in fruit juices to up to 98% in rare cases of spirits.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A standard drink is used globally to quantify alcohol intake, though its definition varies widely by country.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Serving sizes of alcoholic beverages also vary by country.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Alcohol laws regulate the manufacture, packaging, labelling, distribution, sale, consumption, blood alcohol content of motor vehicle drivers, open containers, and transportation of alcoholic drinks.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Such laws generally seek to reduce the adverse health and social impacts of alcohol consumption.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In particular, alcohol laws set the legal drinking age, which usually varies between 15 and 21 years old, sometimes depending upon the type of alcoholic drink (e.g., beer vs wine vs hard liquor or distillates).
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Some countries do not have a legal drinking or purchasing age, but most countries set the minimum age at 18 years.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Some countries, such as the U.S., have the drinking age higher than the legal age of majority (18), at age 21 in all 50 states.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Such laws may take the form of permitting distribution only to licensed stores, monopoly stores, or pubs and they are often combined with taxation, which serves to reduce the demand for alcohol (by raising its price) and it is a form of revenue for governments.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] These laws also often limit the hours or days (e.g., "blue laws") on which alcohol may be sold or served, as can also be seen in the "last call" ritual in US and Canadian bars, where bartenders and servers ask patrons to place their last orders for alcohol, due to serving hour cutoff laws.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In some countries, alcohol cannot be sold to a person who is already intoxicated.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Alcohol laws in many countries prohibit drunk driving.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In some jurisdictions, alcoholic drinks are totally prohibited for reasons of religion (e.g., Islamic countries with sharia law) or for reasons of local option, public health, and morals (e.g., Prohibition in the United States from 1920 to 1933).
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In jurisdictions which enforce sharia law, the consumption of alcoholic drinks is an illegal offense, although such laws may exempt non-Muslims.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Alcohol is used in rum-running, the illegal business of smuggling alcoholic beverages where such transportation is forbidden by law.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Wine fraud relates to the commercial aspects of wine.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The most prevalent type of fraud is one where wines are adulterated, usually with the addition of cheaper products (e.g. juices) and sometimes with harmful chemicals and sweeteners (compensating for color or flavor).
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Moonshine is illegal to produce and sell in most countries.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In Prohibition-era United States, moonshine distillation was done at night to deter discovery.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Once the liquor was distilled, drivers called "runners" or "bootleggers" smuggled moonshine liquor across the region in cars specially modified for speed and load-carrying capacity.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Outbreaks of methanol poisoning have occurred when methanol is used to adulterate moonshine.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In Australia, a sly-grog shop (or shanty) is an unlicensed hotel, liquor-store or other vendor of alcoholic beverages, sometimes with the added connotation of selling poor-quality products.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Pruno also known as prison hooch or prison wine, is a term used in the United States to describe an improvised alcoholic beverage.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] It is variously made from apples, oranges, fruit cocktail, fruit juices, hard candy, sugar, high fructose syrup, and possibly other ingredients, including crumbled bread.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Most countries have laws specifically for the offense of drunk driving.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Driving under the influence (DUI) or driving while intoxicated (DWI), is the crime of driving a motor vehicle while impaired by alcohol or other drugs (including those prescribed by physicians).
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Public intoxication laws vary widely by jurisdiction, but include public nuisance laws, open-container laws, and prohibitions on drinking alcohol in public or certain areas.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Alcohol is a common metabolic by-product formed during the breakdown of sugars in many living cells, though it is typically further metabolised to release additional energy.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Certain yeasts constitute an exception, as they excrete alcohol into their environment, where it acts as a chemical defense against competing microorganisms; this role is analogous to that of lactic acid in fermented foods and aromatic compounds in plants.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] While advantageous to yeast, alcohol is toxic to most cells, and in humans its intoxicating effects result from interference with the normal functioning of brain cells.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Alcohol is a depressant, which in low doses causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] A meta analysis of 107 cohort studies concludes low daily alcohol intake provides no health benefits and increased consumption, even at relatively low levels of daily intake (>2 beverages for women and >3 beverages for men), increases health- and mortality-risks.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Short-term effects of alcohol consumption range from a decrease in anxiety and motor skills and euphoria at lower doses to intoxication (drunkenness), to stupor, unconsciousness, anterograde amnesia (memory "blackouts"), and central nervous system depression at higher doses.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Cell membranes are highly permeable to alcohol, so once it is in the bloodstream, it can diffuse into nearly every cell in the body.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Alcohol can greatly exacerbate sleep problems.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] During abstinence, residual disruptions in sleep regularity and sleep patterns are the greatest predictors of relapse.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Long-term use can lead to an alcohol use disorder, an increased risk of developing physical dependence, cardiovascular disease, and several types of cancer.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Some nations have introduced alcohol packaging warning messages that inform consumers about alcohol and cancer, as well as fetal alcohol syndrome.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] The addition of warning labels on alcoholic beverages is historically supported by organizations of the temperance movement, such as the Woman's Christian Temperance Union, as well as by medical organisations, such as the Irish Cancer Society.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] WHO estimates nearly half of alcohol-attributable cancers in the WHO European Region are linked to light or moderate drinking defined as "less than 1.5 litres of wine or less than 3.5 litres of beer or less than 450 millilitres of spirits per week".
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Public awareness of the link between alcohol consumption and cancer is low in the U.S.
[src:apo-drink/alcohol-drink] Surgeon General argued for the use of cancer warning labels on alcohol products.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] The name of the festival is made up of three terms: "ali" means legumes, "a:yé" - seed, and "lígang" means to sow.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] Meaning the season 'To sow legumes seeds'.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] The festival begins on "Ligange lange", the first Wednesday of "Gimur Polo", which occurs in February in the Gregorian calendar or on Wednesday of the month of Fagun of the Assamese calendar and in the month of February in English calendar which lasts for five days.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] In this festival, young people of the community in particular participate *Gumraag Soman* and dance to the tune of folk songs and melodious *Oi Nitom*.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] The first day of the festival is marked by the ceremonial start of paddy sowing and throughout the festival many others activities such as ploughing and tree cutting are forbidden.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] The last day of festival called as *Lilen* is observed with a grand community feast.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] During this festival, Misings indulge in great banquet with *Po:ro Apong* or *Nogin Apong* (homemade Rice beer) with various dishes, especially made with pork meat.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] *Purang apin* (packed boiled rice) a traditionally prepared dish is served during Ali A:yé Lígang.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] The songs of Ali A:yé Lígang do not remain restricted to the songs of youth alone.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] The subjects and themes of the songs are varied.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] They include the life of a man, his sufferings in this life and his death.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] Apart from them, the songs describe the matters of individual love and affection including joy and pain.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] Mainly the songs of the festival speak of the various experiences of the Misings in their day-to-day life.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] The Music composed for these festivals consists of instruments like the dhul, taal, gong and gungang (gagana).
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] In this festival a popular dance is performed by the young Mising people which is known as "Gumrag".
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] The formal dance of the festival starts from the easternmost house of the village.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] In the end, extending towards the field and the river.
[src:apo-drink/ali-ai-ligang] This dance is performed by encircling the courtyard of the house of the villagers.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Commercial almond milk comes in sweetened, unsweetened, vanilla and chocolate flavors, and is usually fortified with micronutrients as a processed food.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Almond milk can also be made at home using a blender, almonds and water.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Global almond milk sales in 2018 were US$5.8 billion, growing at 14% per year, and forecast to be a $13 billion global market by 2025.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] The earliest recipes for almond milk date back to at least the 13th century Middle East, as it was listed in Muhammad bin Hasan al-Baghdadi’s book *Kitāb al-Ṭabīḫ* (كتاب الطبيخ; *The Book of Dishes*), written in 1226.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Almond milk was used as a substitute for animal milk in the Middle Ages in areas that followed Catholic fasting laws.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Some recipes for almond milk have used wine in the process.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Almond milk's popularity as a dairy substitute continued throughout history, going well into modern times.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] It is even mentioned under the secondary definition of "milk" in Samuel Johnson's *Dictionary* in 1755, alongside pistachio milk.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] In the United States, almond milk remained a niche health food item until the early 2000s, when its popularity began to increase.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] In 2011 alone, almond milk sales increased by 79%.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] In 2013, it surpassed soy milk as the most popular plant-based milk in the US.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] As of 2014 it comprised 60 percent of plant-milk sales and 4.1 percent of total milk sales in the US.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Manufacturers and distributors of animal milk have advocated that plant-based milk not be labelled as "milk".
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] They complain that consumers may be confused between the two, and that plant-based milks are not necessarily as nutritious in terms of vitamins and minerals.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] In the case of the United States, the FDA said in 2023 that plant-based milk could be labeled as milk, but that producers should note the nutritional differences from regular milk.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] European Union regulations require "milk" to be used for animals only, except coconut milk.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Within the Italian regions of Sicily, Apulia, Calabria, and Campania, almond milk is a protected traditional agricultural product.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Vitamin A fortification is only required for skimmed milk in the US.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Vitamin D fortification for milk is mandatory in the US.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] If unfortified, almond milk has less vitamin D than fortified cow milk; in North America, cow milk must be fortified with vitamin D, but vitamins are added to plant milks on a voluntary basis.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Vitamin E is released from the almonds and absorbed.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] The positive effects of the vitamin E include strengthening the cells.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Because of its low protein content (0.4 g per 100 ml), almond milk is not a suitable replacement for breast milk, cow milk, or hydrolyzed formulas for children under two years of age.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] The general production method involves soaking and grinding almonds in an excess of water.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] A milky white liquid is obtained after filtering the almond pulp (flesh).
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Almond milk can also be made by adding water to almond butter.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] In commercial production, almond milk is homogenised with high pressure and pasteurised for greater stability and shelf life.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Almond milk can be stored in the fridge in an air-tight container (preferably a glass container) for about 4–5 days.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] However, certain factors, such as the temperature of the refrigerator, sterilization of the blender or storing jar, and surface cleanliness, can decide how many days you can keep it fresh.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Storing homemade almond milk for more than a week may reduce its nutrition or even make it unhealthy.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] In July 2015, a class action lawsuit was filed in New York City against two American manufacturers, Blue Diamond Growers and White Wave Foods, for false advertising regarding the small quantity of almonds (only 2%) contained in the final product.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] In October 2015, a judge denied the plaintiff's request for an injunction.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Almond production in California is concentrated mainly in the Central Valley, where the mild climate, rich soil, and abundant sunshine and water supply make for ideal growing conditions.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Due to the persistent droughts in California in the early 21st century, it became more difficult to raise almonds in a sustainable manner.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Almond sustainability is challenged because of the high amount of water needed to grow almonds: a single glass of almond milk requires roughly 74 litres (16 imp gal; 20 US gal) of water to produce.
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Among plant-based milks, almond milk requires substantially more water during the growing and production stages than soy, rice or oat milk (graph).
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] Dairy milk requires more water to produce than almond milk (graph).
[src:apo-drink/almond-milk] In 2014, California produced 42.3 billion pounds of cow's milk and only 2.14 billion pounds of almond milk.
[src:apo-drink/amazake] There are several recipes for *amazake* that have been used for hundreds of years.
[src:apo-drink/amazake] By a popular recipe, *kōji* is added to cooled whole grain rice causing enzymes to break down the carbohydrates into simpler unrefined sugars.
[src:apo-drink/amazake] As the mixture incubates, sweetness develops naturally.
[src:apo-drink/amazake] By another recipe, sake kasu is mixed with water and sugar is added.
[src:apo-drink/amazake] Similar beverages include the Chinese *jiuniang* which is more pudding like and Korean *gamju* or *sikhye*.
[src:apo-drink/amazake] In grape winemaking, must – sweet, thick, unfermented grape juice – is a similar product.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Many tribal communities of Arunachal Pradesh use apo during their respective festivals, such as nyokum.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The tribal people offer the drink, every time they drink it, to the uiyu (spirits) by letting a few drops of it fall on the ground.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Other occasions when Apo is served include annually organized ancestor worship ceremonies, the festivals of Ali aye ligang, Nyokum, Dree, and others, and annual agricultural programs.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Apo is known in different names across different tribes in North-Eastern India, such as haaz (Ahom), apong (Mising), zou (zu mai) (Bodo) and Sujen (Deori).
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Apo is not distributed in shops, as apo forms part of a tradition and culture, the apo is shared through generations like a piece of cultural knowledge.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Apos are commonly brewed in households and often served along with rice and chutney as well, irrespective of gender or age differences.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The origins of the apo tradition in the North-Eastern regions are not recorded, However, the tradition may date back to Neolithic period.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Similarly, the word Apo is not a general term for a rice-based drink, as each tribe identifies the drink with different names.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] However, it is believed that the traditional rice beer was first developed by the 'Mising people in Assam.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Thus the etymology of the word refers to its Mising language origins.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Across the different tribes, the brewing method has certain differences, but the substrates used for fermentation are the same.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] This indicates a common ancestor to the brewing culture in North-Eastern India.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Traditionally, two kinds of Apo are being brewed in these regions known as Po:ro Apong and Nogin Apong.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The starter cakes called épob are made out of crushed rice and medicinal plants are used to make the health quotient.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] These starter cakes are one of the most important elements of the rice beers made in the North-Eastern region, including Apo.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] This also refers to the idea of sacredness associated with the Apo making across different tribes as it is not made on an everyday basis, but only for ceremonies, festivals, marriage, and group gatherings.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] In this regard, historically and culturally, the Apo remains as an element of identity in these regions.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Apo is known in different traditional names based on the respective tribes.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Apo is believed to be first developed by the Mising people in Assam.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The term Apo is derived from the traditional name "Apong" in the Mising language.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The Mising community is generally known for its passion for traditional cooking methods and food items.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The cooking method of the Apo is also believed to be shared by the ancestors of Mising community and later spread throughout the tribes in North East India.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Apo is commonly produced in households of northeastern states of Arunachal Pradesh and Assam in India.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Although distinctive methods for brewing exist across the North-Eastern region of India, the process of fermentation remains the same across these regions, indicating common origins of brewing.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] As a first step, the rice collected for making beverage is cooked and then mixed with ash from burnt paddy sticks, which makes the mixture black.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Once the rice is cooked, it is mixed with the fermenting ingredient E-Pob made out of rice and medicinal plants.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Time is taken for the formation of ration changes along with the climate and temperature.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] During summer, the fermentation took 5–6 days.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The fermented mixture is filtered and finally poured into bamboo shoots.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] During these processes, around 30 medicinal plants use to the beverage along with rice.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] This includes leaves, creepers, and grass.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The total period taken for the production of Apo beer is more than 3 months.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Although the alcohol content on the Apo is 18-25% it is more intoxicating in nature.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Recent studies indicate the Apo Beer can be economically benefiting the community as the beer provides the entrepreneurial potential to the community as the rice beer produced in Northeast regions, including Apo are high quality in nature.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The starter cake is one of the most indispensable elements of the Apo beer production process.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The Apo beer produced by the Mising community is identified to have various medicinal and therapeutic properties as a result often used during the preparation of starter cake known as épob.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The beer-making process in each tribe varies according to the environmental factors and other socio-cultural practices associated with the individual tribes.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] These factors are essential in determining the colour, flavour, and sweetness of the flower.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] One major process during the production of Apong is the use of starter cake, i.e. épob which has significant medicinal qualities.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] This quality is of starter cake is determined by the medicinal plants used during the production along with the sanitary conditions used while making the beer.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The making of épob in this regard include the process of collecting a variety of medicinal plant leaves.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The leaves collected are dried placing it on a bamboo mat known as époh after cleaning it.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Fresh leaves can also be used for making the starter cake for making the beer.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The leaves are later ground separately using a wooden tool hand mixer together to make an épob in the shape of oval-shaped balls from the dough made from the mixture.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The folk medicine beliefs of the starter cake derive from the use of local herbs.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Tribes believe that the combination of herbs makes Apo beer an effective agent against various minor diseases.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Most of the plants used for the preparation of the beer are indigenous.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The varieties of Apo beer in the northeast region of India include methods of infusion and decoction used by the local peoples.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Apo is an important element in the socio-cultural aspect of the Mising people.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] The Apo beer is served during religious festivals and ceremonies in Assam such as Marriages, death ceremonies, Ali A:yé Lígang, Porag, and other major community gatherings and celebration.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Apong is usually served along with pork and Purang apin in festivals like Ali A:yé Lígang.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] In local markets, Apo beer is a source of income and livelihood for many families, and contributes to community development.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] In Assam, it has been reportedly found to be sold by local brewers in small bottles.
[src:apo-drink/apo-drink] Apo was featured in the Indian Amazon Prime Video web series *The Family Man* (season 3), where it is depicted as a traditional rice-based alcoholic beverage consumed in Northeast India.
